<subSubSection pageId="63" pageNumber="64" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="63" pageNumber="64">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="63" pageNumber="64">
It is unlikely this belongs to 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. chapelieri" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" rank="species" species="chapelieri">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">C. chapelieri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(in which 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. daphniphylloides" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" rank="species" species="daphniphylloides">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">C. daphniphylloides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is treated here as a synonym); it occurs in the Marojejy Reserve at 500 m elevation and is a 8 m tall tree, whereas 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. chapelieri" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" rank="species" species="chapelieri">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">C. chapelieri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is confined to the eastern littoral zone near sea level. It could also be a northern form of 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. submetallicus" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" rank="species" species="submetallicus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">C. submetallicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, with more acute leaves and lacking the submetallic leaf undersides of that species.
</paragraph>
